==English==

===Etymology===
From {{etyl|la|en}} {{term|lang=la|applaudere||to clap the hands together, applaud}}, from {{term|lang=la|ad||to}} + {{term|lang=la|plaudere||to strike, clap}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|UK}} {{IPA|/əˈplɔːd/}}, {{X-SAMPA|/@"plO:d/}}
* {{a|US}} {{IPA|/əˈplɔd/}}, {{X-SAMPA|/@"plOd/}}
* {{a|cot-caught}} {{IPA|/əˈplɑd/}}, {{X-SAMPA|/@"plAd/}}
* {{audio|en-us-applaud.ogg|Audio (US)}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# {{context|obsolete|lang=en}} [[applause|Applause]]; applauding.
# {{context|obsolete|lang=en}} [[plaudit|Plaudit]].

====Related terms====
* [[applause]]

===Verb===
{{en-verb}}

# {{context|transitive|intransitive|lang=en}} To [[express]] [[approval]] (of something) by [[clap|clapping]] the [[hand]]s.
#: ''After the performance, the audience '''applauded''' for five minutes''
# {{context|transitive|intransitive|lang=en}} To [[praise]], or express approval for something or someone.
#: ''Although we don't like your methods, we '''applaud''' your motives.''
